            "programStructure": {
                "S": "<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n\n<ol>\n\t<li><strong>Getting Start</strong></li>\n</ol>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>What is Kali Linux</li>\n\t<li>Booting a Kali ISO Image in Live Mode</li>\n\t<li>Using Kali Linux with Virtual Machine</li>\n\t<li>Installing Kali Linux from Scratch</li>\n</ul>\n\n<ol>\n\t<li><strong>Kali Linux Fundamental</strong></li>\n</ol>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>Kali GUI/Desktop</li>\n\t<li>Kali CLI/Terminal</li>\n\t<li>Type of Shells</li>\n\t<li>Linux FileSystem Hierachy</li>\n\t<li>Linux Environment Variables</li>\n\t<li>Basic Limux Command</li>\n\t<li>Text Processing Tools</li>\n\t<li>Manage Network Interface</li>\n\t<li>Configuring Common Services (SSH, PostgreSQL, Apache)</li>\n\t<li>Introduction to APT</li>\n\t<li>Kali Repositorie</li>\n\t<li>Installing Packages with APT</li>\n\t<li>Installing Packages with dpkg</li>\n</ul>\n\n<ol>\n\t<li><strong>Users, Groups and Permissions</strong></li>\n</ol>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>Explain the LINUX security model</li>\n\t<li>Explain the purpose of user and group accounts</li>\n\t<li>Read and set file permissions</li>\n\t<li>Describe where Linux stores user, group and password information</li>\n\t<li>Change identities</li>\n\t<li>Set default permissions</li>\n\t<li>Use special permissions</li>\n</ul>\n\n<ol>\n\t<li><strong>Kali Linux for Hacking</strong></li>\n</ol>\n\n<ul>\n\t<li>Types of Assessments</li>\n\t<li>Vulnerability Assessment</li>\n\t<li>Impact</li>\n\t<li>Overall Risk</li>\n\t<li>Traditional Penetration Test</li>\n\t<li>Application Assessment</li>\n\t<li>Types of Attacks</li>\n\t<li>Denial of Service</li>\n\t<li>Memory Corruption</li>\n\t<li>Web Vulnerabilities</li>\n\t<li>Password Attacks</li>\n\t<li>Client-Side Attacks</li>\n</ul>\n"
            },
